column168: THE FREIGHT WAS FOUND LEAKING. THERE WAS NO POSITIVE CLOSURE ON THE FRICTION-LID CAN. THE SHIPPER PROVIDED TWO MSDS, BOTH SHOWED THE COMMODITY TO BE FLAMMABLE. THE SHIPPER ALSO SAID THE FREIGHT WAS SUPPOSED TO TRAVEL BY GROUND. I'VE EXPLAINED THAT TO USE FEDEX GROUND YOU NEED AN ACCOUNT, THIS SHIPPER HAS NO SUCH ACCOUNT, AND THEY COMPETED AN AIR WAYBILL. THEY FINALLY AGREED THEY GOOFED. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE FAA/TSA WAS NOTIFIED & THE FREIGHT HELD PENDING AN INSPECTION.

SYNOPSIS: RAILCAR UTLX 28475 (WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS) NEW ORLEANS PUBLIC BELT RAILROAD ON MONDAY JULY 8, 2002 AT APPROXIMATELY 03:00 HOURS, UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, L.L.C. (USES) RESPONDED AT THE REQUEST OF THE NEW ORLEANS PUBLIC BELT RAILROAD (NOPBRR), MR. JOE BERTUCCI, TO A TANK CAR LOCATED AT THEIR NEW ORLEANS, LA FACILITY, GIVING OFF AN ODOR. UPON ARRIVAL IT WAS NOTED THAT THE NEW ORLEANS FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS  TEAM (NOFD)  AND HARBOR POLICE DEPARTMENT WERE ON SITE.  USES REPRESENTATIVE, MR FRANK PIEDISCALZO, MET WITH THE NOFD AND MR. BERTUCCI AND DISCUSSED THE SITUATION. MR. BERTUCCI INFORMED MR. PIEDISCALZO THAT THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM A GROUP OF CARS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND THEY WERE UNSURE AS TO WHICH ONE IT WAS MR. PIEDISCALZO AND A REPRESENTATIVE FOR THE RAILROAD WALKED DOWN THE TRACKS TO THE CARS IN QUESTION. ALONG THE PATH MR. PIEDISCALZO WAS CONDUCTING AIR MONITORING TO DETERMINE IF ANY LEL'S EXISTED BECAUSE 5 OF THE 6 CARS CONTAINED A FLAMMABLE MATERIAL. AS THEY APPROACHED THE CARS A SLIGHT PUNGENT ODOR WAS DETECTED BUT THE METER DETECTED NO READINGS. MR. PIEDISCALZO EXAMINED THE CARS ONE BY ONE AND NOTICED NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF A LEAK BUT DID NOTICE THAT THE ODOR WAS NOT CONSISTENT WITH THE PRODUCTS CONTAINED IN 5 OF THE 6 TANK CARS. MR. PIEDISCALZO THEN DECIDED TO CHECK THE RAILCAR IN QUESTION (UTLX 28475). MR. PIEDISCALZO BROKE THE DOME SEAL AND HE NOTICED THE ODOR BECAME STRONGER WHEN THE LID WAS OPENED CONFIRMING THAT THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM THIS CAR. AFTER A VISUAL INSPECTION IT WAS DETERMINED AT THE POINT THAT THE ODOR MAY BE COMING FROM RESIDUAL PRODUCT  AROUND THE LIQUID LINE. MR. PIEDISCALZO CLOSED THE LID AND AT THE REQUEST OF THE RAILROAD REPRESENTATIVE AND THE APPROVAL OF THE NOFD THE CAR WOULD BE MOVED TO A SAFER LOCATION IN ORDER TO REOPEN THE RAIL YARD AND SECURE THE ODOR SOURCE. THE RAILCAR WAS MOVED TO A SECLUDED TRACK AWAY FROM ANY PEDESTRIAN AND COMMERCIAL TRAFFIC. THE NOFD AND THE HARBOR POLICE DEPARTED THE SCENE. MR. PIEDISCALZO THEN CLIMBED THE CAR WITH THE INTENTIONS OF CLEANING UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND MAKING SURE THAT THERE NO OTHER SOURCES FOR THE ODOR. MR. PIEDISCALZO INSTALLED A PRESSURE GAUGE ON THE CAR AS TO CHECK THE PRESSURE AND NOTICED IT WAS AT 45 PSI. HE THEN USED A SOLUTION TO CHECK FOR LEAKS AROUND ANY OF THE FITTINGS INSIDE OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. AS HE APPLIED THE SOLUTION IT WAS QUICKLY NOTED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE (SRV) WAS LEAKING. MR. PIEDISCALZO INFORMED THE NOPBRR REPRESENTATIVE THAT THE SRV'S CAP AND O-RINGS WOULD NEED TO BE REPLACED. MR. PIEDISCALZO THEN REMOVED THE CAP AND O-RINGS AND REPLACED THEM WITH NEW ONES. THE SRV WAS THEN RECHECKED FOR LEAKS. NO LEAKS WERE DETECTED. THE RESIDUAL PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED BY THE RAILROAD AT APPROXIMATELY 07:00 HOURS. MR. PIEDISCALZO RETAINED THE OLD CAP AND O-RINGS FOR INSPECTION PURPOSES AND USES DEPARTED THE SITE.

column168: WHILE MAKING THE SECOND DELIVERY OF THE DAY INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK, THE DRIVER FOUND THAT THE STORAGE TANK FILL DRAIN VALVE WAS INADVERTENTLY LEFT OPEN. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE FILL LINE INLET VALVE AND SHUT OFF THE CARGO TANK'S UNLOADING PUMP. APPROXIMATELY 475 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS DISCHARGE INTO THE TANK'S CONTAINMENT DIKE BEFORE THE DRIVER FOUND THE VALVE WAS OPEN. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS DILUTED WITH WATER AND THE CUSTOMER NOTIFIED. THE CUSTOMER DISPOSED OF THE DILUTED MATERIAL INTO THEIR FACILITY TREATMENT SYSTEM. THE DELIVERY WAS COMPLETED WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENT. SINCE THIS DRAIN VALVE IS NOT USED OR NEEDED IN THE FILL LINE SYSTEM, THE CUSTOMER WILL REMOVE THE VALVE FROM THEIR FILL LINE SYSTEM. UNTIL THE DRAIN VALVE IS REMOVED, THE VALVE WILL BE LOCKED CLOSED FOR FUTURE DELIVERIES. THIS WILL PREVENT THE POSSIBILITY OF INADVERTENTLY LEAVING THE VALVE OPEN.

SUPERIOR TRUCK DRIVER MISTAKENLY PULLED AWAY FROM THE UNLOADING STATION WHILE STILL CONNECTED. RESULTED IN A SPILL FROM THE REAR VALVE OF THE TRAILER APPROXIMATELY 123 YARDS NORTH ON THE PLANT ROAD UNTIL HE COULD BE STOPPED AND THE VALVE CLOSED. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND WASHED DOWN TO STORMWATER CONTAINMENT AND THEN SENT THROUGH THE PLANT WASTE WATER TREATMENT UNIT. DRIVER TRAINING AND TRUCK LOADING/UNLOADING PROCEDURES BEING REVISED TO INSURE PHYSICAL CONTROL OF TRUCKS DURING FILLING AND OFF. LOADING OPERATIONS.

DRIVER OVER STEERED AT THIS TIME CAUSING VEHICLE TO REENTER HIGHWAY AT AN ANGLE CAUSING VEHICLE TO ROLL ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE AND SLIDE ON THE PAVEMENT. SLIDING ON THE PAVEMENT RIPPED HOLES IN TRAILER CAUSING RELEASE OF ENTIRE LOAD. NO OTHER VEHICLES INVOLVED. DRIVER TREATED & RELEASED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRUM WAS FOUND LEAKING ON TRAILER LOADED BY SHIPPER LOOKS AS IF IT WAS PUNCTURED BY NAIL IN FLOOR.

AFTER DRIVER COMPLETED OFFLOADING OF PRODUCT, HE TRIPPED OVER A BUCKET THAT WAS USED TO CATCH AND LIQUID THAT MAY HAVE LEAKED FROM THE PUMP. HE KNOCKED OVER A BUCKET THAT HE WAS USING AND ALSO A BUCKET THAT BELONGED TO THE CUSTOMER. THIS RESULTED IN A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS. A REMEDIATION COMPANY WAS CALLED TO THE SITE TO CONDUCT A CLEANUP.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column42: SELF-REACTIVE SOLID TYPE C, TEMPERATURE CONTROLLED
column168: WHILE STOPPED AT A REST STOP OFF INTERSTATE 81, AN ALARM WAS DETECTED GOING OFF INSIDE THE TRAILER. THE ROCKBRIDGE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. THE AREA WAS EVACUATED UNTIL THE CAUSE OF THE ALARM COULD BE DETECTED. HAZMAT 2000, INC. OF STAUNTON, VIRGINA WAS DISPATCHED TO INSPECT THE TRAILER. UPON INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER BY HAZMAT 2000, INC. AND THE ROCKBRIDGE FIRE DEPARTMENT, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT NO RELEASE OCCURRED. APPARENTLY, THE SUSPECTED RELEASE WAS CAUSED  BY A FAULTY ALARM ON THE REFRIGERATION UNIT INSIDE THE TRAILER. THE REFRIGERATION UNIT CONTAINED 150 DRUMS OF SELF-REACTIVE SOLID TYPE C,  TEMPERATURE CONTROLLED. THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE FREIGHT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE TRAILER WAS SENT ON TO IT'S DESTINATION.

column62: Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: UPON ARRIVING AT THE CONSIGNEE LOCATION, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED COMING FROM THE INTERMODAL STEEL CONTAINER ON THE TRAILER. THE SHIPMENT WAS REFUSED AND SENT NEXT DOOR TO THE PACIFIC RIM TRANSPORT, INC. FACILITY IN TACOMA, WASHINGTON.  FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OF SEATTLE, WASHINGTON WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER, ONE FIFTY-FIVE  GALLON DRUM WAS FOUND DAMAGED IN THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER. APPARENTLY, THE DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A PROTRUDING NAIL AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT INSIDE THE CONTAINER AND ON THE DIRT PARKING LOT. FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND SIMPLE GREEN TO THE FREE PRODUCT. THE CONTAINER WAS OFFLOADED AND CLEANED. FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ALSO EXCAVATED THE CONTAMINATED DIRT FROM THE LOT. DISPOSAL  WILL BE COORDINATED PER LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

column168: ROCKY MOUNT YARD CREW NOTICED ODOR FROM PLMX2503 AT 1245 HOURS ON JULY7, 2002. CSX TRANSPORTATION MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THE CORPORATIONS EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLANS. ALL REGULATORY AGENCIES ALONG WITH CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED. THE SHIPPER, CF INDUSTRIES WAS CONTACTED. HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL WAS REQUESTED TO RESPOND TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE. INVESTIGATION REVEALS THAT THE CAR DEVELOPED A BREACH BETWEEN THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND PRESSURE PLATE. ACTUAL CAUSE IS BELIEVED TO BE A DETERIORATED PRESSURE PLATE GASKET. HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL PERFORMED AIR MONITORING UNTIL TRANSFER OF PRODUCT WAS COMPLETE. PETROCLEAN ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSFERRED THE PRODUCT INTO TANK CAR CITX34522 ON JULY 9, 2002. ESTIMATED LOSS OF PRODUCT: 20 POUNDS. NO ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION REQUIRED. NARRI SCORE: 210 5*(5+9+0)*(3+0) CAUSE CODE: 221.

column168: A CSX TRANSPORTATION TRAIN CREW WAS HANDLING TANK CAR UTLX 644100 IN THE LOCUST POINT YARD WHEN THEY OBSERVED LIQUID SLOSHING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. THE TRAIN CREW STOPPED MOVEMENT OF THE TANK CAR AND NOTIFIED THE YARD SUPERVISOR OF THEIR OBSERVATION. THE SUPERVISOR CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE AND THE CSXT OPERATIONS CENTER. CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER GORTON RESPONDED TO THE YARD AND INSPECTED THE TANK CAR. A SMALL RESIDUE OF PRODUCT WAS OBSERVED ON TOP OF THE CAR BUT WAS NOT DRIPPING TO THE GROUND. THE MANWAY COVER WAS UNBOLTED AND INSPECTED. THE INSPECTION SHOWED THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS MISSING. THE LACK OF A GASKET ALLOWED LIQUID PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM UNDER THE LID WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED. THE CONSIGNEE WAS NOTIFIED OF THE CAR'S CONDITION AND ASKED TO SUPPLY A GASKET FOR THE MANWAY. A NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE MANWAY LID WAS TIGHTENED AND CHECKED FOR LEAKS. FINDING NO FURTHER LEAKS THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE BOX WAS DISCOVERED CRUSHED. ONE INNER BOTTLE HAD LEAKED EMPTY AND SPILLAGE HAD EVAPORATED. THE BOX WAS RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

THE CONSIGNEE WAS CONTACTED AND DISPATCHED PERSONNEL TO THE SCENE. UPON ARRIVAL, PENN SPECIALTY CHEMICAL PERSONNEL FOUND EIGHT OF EIGHT MANWAY BOLTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED, SECURING THE TANK CAR AND ELIMINATING THE LEAK WHEN THE CAR IS IN MOTION.
THREE DRUMS WERE CRUSHED BY HEAVY TOP FREIGHT. THE DRUMS WERE RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

UTLX 801624 WAS DISCOVERED WITH A LEAK AT APPROXIMATELY 0500, JULY 15, 2002 IN THE CSX TRANSPORTATION RAIL YARD, DANVILLE, IL. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED. column42: DANGEROUS GOODS IN MACHINERY OR DANGEROUS GOODS IN APPARATUS
column168: THERE WAS NO SPILL OF ANY KIND.  THE SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED TO LAX CARGO AS "MACHINE PARTS" - NON DANGEROUS GOODS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PROCESSED FOR THE FLIGHT AND WAS LOADED ON THE AIRCRAFT.  THE SHIPPER CONTACTED THE AA CARGO RESERVATIONS TO ADVISE THEY BELIEVED THE SHIPMENT TO CONTAIN A DANGEROUS GOOD.  LAX CARGO WAS CONTACTED AND IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE RAMP CREW IN CHARGE OF LOADING THE SHIPMENT ON THE AIRCRAFT.  AT THE TIME OF NOTIFICATION, THE SHIPMENT WAS ALREADY LOADED ABOARD THE AIRCRAFT.  THE AIRCRAFT WAS CLOSED UP AND WAS IN THE PROCESS OF BEING PUSHED BACK.  THE AA SUPERVISOR CONTACTED THE PUSHBACK CREW TO RETURN THE AIRCRAFT TO THE GATE FOR REMOVAL OF THE SHIPMENT.  THE REMOVAL PROCESS CAUSED A 24 MINUTE DEPARTURE DELAY FOR FLIGHT - HENCE THIS FORM.  THE EVENT WAS REPORTED TO THE FAA AND CLEARED FOR RECOVERY BY THE SHIPPER.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED BY LAX CARGO SALES.  THE MATTER WAS DISCUSSED AND MADE CLEAR TO THE SHIPPER THAT AMERICAN AIRLINES CANNOT ACCEPT ERRORS SUCH AS THIS HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED CARTON CONTAINING NINE, ONE QUART PLASTIC PAILS WAS DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK FLOOR. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THREE PAILS WERE DAMAGED AND SIX WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY THREE QUARTS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT BEING LOADED ON TOP WHICH CRUSHED THE TOP OF THE PAILS. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND DAMAGED PAILS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE SIX UNAFFECTED PAILS WERE REPACKAGED AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED ONE HUNDRED POUND PLASTIC BAG WAS DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TWO POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE WQAS DUE TO THE BAG BEING PUNCTURED BY AN ADJACENT SKID IN THE TRAILER. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, A BROOM AND A DUSTPAN. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PALCED INTO ONE, THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE DMAAGED BAG WAS TAPED UP AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE  ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXSPOURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, TWO DAMAGED FIFTY POUND PLASTIC BAGS WERE DISCOVERED ON A PALLET INSIDE THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY EIGHT CUPS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE DOCK. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A NAIL ON THE PALLET. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING A TYVEK SUIT, DUSTMASK, GOGGLES, GLOVES, A DUSTPAN AND BROOM. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE TWO DAMAGED BAGS WERE RECOUPED AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED ONE (1) FIFTY-POUND BAG WHICH HAD A RIP IN THE BOTTOM  CORNER. APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES WERE RELEASED. TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM SWEPT UP THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL. THE DAMAGED BAG WAS PLACED INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM ALONG WITH THE FREE PRODUCT. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A TEN-GALLON RECOVERY DRUM INCLUDING TYVEK SUITS, BOOTIES, GLOVES, CARTRIDGE FILTERS, DUCT TAPE, ABSORBENT PADS, AND DUST PAN AND BROOM. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. TERMINAL PENDING DISPOSITION. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIVE GALLON PLASTIC PAIL WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT, DAMAGING THE PAIL'S LID. TERMINAL PERSONAL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND PAPER TOWELS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO THE TERMINAL'S WASTE RECEPTACLE. THE LEAKING PAIL WILL BE HELD WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT AT THE TERMINAL, AWAITING CONSIGNEE PICKUP. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING THREE HUNDRED AND THIRTY GALLON PLASTIC TOTE WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRAILER. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A FORKLIFT PUNCTURE. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THIS DAMAGE OCCURRED PRIOR TO THE TOTE BEING RECEIVED BY ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE. TERMINAL PERSONNEL LIFTED THE TOTE WITH A PALLET-HOLDER AND PLACED A PLASTIC BUCKET UNDERNEATH IT TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT. H.M.H.T.T.C. OF HARRISBURG, PENNSYLVANIA RESPONDED TO THE TERMINAL TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP AND WILL COORDINATE DISPOSITION OF WASTE GENERATED. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING THIRTY GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK. APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND DRIED ON SURROUNDING DUNNAGE. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PACKAGING FAILURE DUE TO BEING OVERFILLED BY THE SHIPPER. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS ISOLATED. DAVID HEYDT OF ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. DISPATCHED H.M.H.T.T.C. OF HARRISBURG, PA TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. H.M.H.T.T.C. REMOVED THE AFFECTED DUNNAGE, RECOUPED THE DRUM AND TIGHTENED THE CLOSURE TO PREVENT FURTHER RELEASE. THE LEAKING DRUM IS BEING HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE AT THE CARLISLE TRUCK STOP OFF ROUTE 41 IN CARLISLE, INDIANA, THE DRIVER NOTICED FREE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, ONE WET FIBERBOARD CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, FIVE GALLON METAL PAIL WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT ONE PAIL WAS LEAKING AND THE REMAINING THREE PAILS WERE AFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE ASPHALT.  THE DAMAGE TO THE CARTON WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT, CAUSING THE CARTON TO RUB AGAINST THE LOAD BAR AND DENT THE PAIL.  HAZMAT ONE OF OLATHE, KANSAS WAS CONTACTED BY ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. TO COORDINATE THE CLEANUP.  SUMMIT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. OF EVANSVILLE, INDIANA RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING TYVEK SUITS, ABSORBENTS, A SHOVEL AND A BROOM.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND LEAKING PAIL WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WAS RETURNED TO THE SUMMIT ENVIRONMENTAL FACILITY FOR DISPOSITION COORDINATION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES NO EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

CF PERSONNEL WERE UNLOADING A TRAILER WHEN PERSONNEL DISCOVERED LEAKING MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE MATERIAL WAS MOVED INTO A SECURED AREA. A RESPONSE TEAM WAS CONTACTED TO CLEAN THE TRAILER AND REPACKAGE THE MATERIAL. THE TEAM ARRIVED ONSITE AND BEGAN REPACKAGING THE PALLETS. THREE SACK WERE REMOVED FROM THE LOAD. THESE SACKS WERE PLACED INTO A WASTE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. THE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL LOST WAS MINIMAL.  THE DAMAGED PACKAGES COULD NOT BE REPAIRED FOR SHIPMENT. THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLEANED OF ALL WASTE. ALL WASTE WAS PLACED INTO ONE WASTE DRUM FOR FUTURE DISPOSAL .

AT 6:30 AM ON WEDNESDAY JULY 10, 2002, WHILE LOADING TOLUENE (CAS NO. 108-88-3) FROM A BULK STORAGE TANK INTO A STAINLESS STEEL TANK TRUCK, THE TOLUENE VAPORS EXPLODED. THE ENSUING FIRE WAS QUICKLY EXTINGUISHED BY A WATER DELUGE SYSTEM IN PLACE AT THE LOADING FACILITY. FOLLOW UP INVESTIGATION INDICATES THAT APPROXIMATELY 55 GALLONS (399 POUNDS) OF TOLUENE WOULD HAVE BEEN RELEASED FROM THE PIPING SYSTEM  BEFORE THE DELUGE SYSTEM AUTOMATICALLY TURNED OFF THE LOADING PUMP (AN ESTIMATED 15 TO 20 SECONDS). THAT 55 GALLONS WAS APPARENTLY BURNED UP IN THE FIRE. TO THE BEST THAT WE CAN DETERMINE, THERE WAS NO RELEASE TO THE GROUND. THERE WAS A TRACE OF TOLUENE IN THE FIRE SPRINKLER WATER, ALL OF WHICH WAS RECOVERED FROM THE CONTAINMENT AREA. ALL OF THAT WATER WAS COLLECTED AND SENT FOR TREATMENT/DISPOSAL AT A PROPERLY PERMITTED FACILITY. TOLUENE IS NOT AN EHS. BECAUSE THE INTENTION WAS TO LOAD 10,875 POUNDS OF TOLUENE INTO THE TANK TRUCK, AND THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY IS 1,000 POUNDS, IT IS CLASSIFIED AS A HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE. AN ESTIMATED 2,175 LBS HAD BEEN LOADED INTO THE TRUCK BEFORE THE PUMP WAS AUTOMATICALLY SHUT OFF. THE TANK TRUCK INTEGRITY WAS NOT COMPROMISED IN ANY WAY AND ALL OF THIS TOLUENE REMAINED IN THE TRUCK. TWO EMPLOYEES WERE BURNED, ONE FATALLY. HE SUCCUMBED TO THE BURNS ABOUT 12 HOURS AFTER THE FIRE. THE OTHER EMPLOYEE WAS IN THE HOSPITAL FOR ABOUT TWO WEEKS AND IS NOW AT HOME RECOVERING AND UNDERGOING FURTHER MEDICAL TREATMENT AND THERAPY. THE CITY OF BEDFORD PARK FIRE DEPARTMENT HAS A STATION RIGHT AT THE ENTRANCE TO THE TERMINAL. IT IS ROUGHLY 600 YARDS FROM THE UNIVAR FACILITY. THE AUTOMATIC SYSTEMS AT THE UNIVAR FACILITY ALSO SOUNDED THE ALARM FOR THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE UNIVAR FACILITY WAS IMMEDIATELY EVACUATED. I HEARD OF THE INCIDENT AT 9:00 AM. AT THAT TIME IT WAS THOUGHT THAT SOMEONE ELSE HAD CALLED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, AND THE ILLINOIS EPA. I TOOK OUT MY EMERGENCY RESPONSE NOTIFICATION FILE AND CALLED THE ILLINOIS EPA AT APPROX. 9:05 AM. THE PERSON I TALKED TO HAD KNOWLEDGE OF THE FIRE EMERGENCY. I DID NOT ATTEMPT TO DETERMINE WHEN OR WHERE OR HOW THEY HAD RECEIVED THE INFORMATION. THE NUMBER I CALLED WAS (217 782-7860. AT APPROXIMATELY 9:10 AM I CALLED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER. IN CONVERSATIONS WITH THEM THEY DID NOT SHOW THAT ANYONE HAD CALLED THEM, FROM ILLINOIS. THEY TOOK THE AVAILABLE FIRE/RELEASE INFORMATION FROM ME AT THE TIME AND IT WAS LOGGED AS THEIR NUMBER 616192, BY AGENT BENNETT. ABOUT 15 MINUTES LATER, I RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE US EPA REGION 5 OFFICE. I BELIEVE THE PERSON'S NAME WAS THOMAS COOK.  I EXPLAINED THAT THE FIRE WAS OUT AND THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCIES WERE ON SITE. ADDITIONALLY, I EXPLAINED THAT THERE WAS CONTAINMENT AND THAT THERE WAS NO CONTINUING RELEASE, AND THAT THE ILLINOIS EPA HAD KNOWLEDGE OF THE INCIDENT AND WAS PROBABLY IN CONTACT WITH THE LOCAL EMERGENCY  RESPONSE OFFICIALS(BEDFORD PARK FD). column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE, LYONDELL CHEMICAL COMPANY, ON INTERSTATE 10 IN LAKE CHARLES, LOUISIANA, THE DRIVER NOTICED THE HOSE ON HIS CARGO TANKER STARTING  TO LEAK AS THE PRODUCT WAS BEING TRANSFERRED FROM THE TANKER TO THE CUSTOMER'S  TANK. APPROXIMATELY TWO QUARTS OF FREE PRODUCT LEAKED INTO A FIVE GALLON PLASTIC BUCKET, WHICH THE DRIVER HAD PLACED DOWN UNDER THE LEAK TO PREVENT ANY ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT. THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS FROM AN UNKNOWN CAUSE. THE FIVE GALLON PLASTIC BUCKET WAS HELD AT LYONDELL CHEMICAL COMPANY FOR DISPOSITION. LYONDELL CHEMICAL COMPANY WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE FIVE GALLON PLASTIC BUCKET. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED. ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.

UN-APPARENT CRACK IN 2-INCH REDUCER FITTING FROM OUR TRANSFER HOSE TO THE CUSTOMERS TANK.  UPON PRESSURIZATION BY PUMP-OFF ACTION FITTING FAILED CAUSING 15-20 GALLON SPILL.  CLEANED UP BY CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL AND DISPOSED OF BY CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL.

WHILE LOADING AT OUR LENEXA TERMINAL, A FORKLIFT BLADE PUNCTURED ONE DRUM CAUSING A LEAK.  THE DRUM AND CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM.  WE RECEIVED AUTHORIZATION FROM THE SHIPPER AND IT IS BEING HELD FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

DRIVER UNLOADING USING A DRUMMING NOZZLE.  DID NOT KNOW NOZZLE NEEDED TO BE SCREWED IN AND WHEN PLANT UNLOADER STARTED TO UNLOAD NOZZLE DISCONNECTED AND PRODUCT SPRAYED.  PRODUCT GOT ON DRIVER AND UNLOADER.  BOTH OK.  DRIVER TAKEN TO MEDICAL CENTER TO BE CHECKED OUT.  NO LOST TIME.
UNLOADER OPENED CUSTOMER VALVE PRIOR TO FINAL HOSE HOOK UP.  NO PHYSICAL CONTACT WITH PRODUCT.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ACCIDENT IS UNDER INVESTIGATION AT THIS TIME.  FOR SOME REASON, THE CTS DRIVER STRUCK AN INDIANA DEPT OF TRANSPORTATION PICKUP.  AFTER STRIKING THE PICKUP, THE CTS TRACTOR / TRAILER RAN OFF THE ROAD AND OVERTURNED IN THE DITCH.  SOUTH BEND, IN. FIRE DEPT. AND THE INDIAN STATE POLICE RESPONDED. THEY CONTACTED SUNPRO ENVIRONMENTAL TO ASSIST WITH THE SPILLED PAINT.  THE CTS DRIVER AND IDOT EMPLOYEES WERE TREATED AND RELEASED FROM THE SOUTH BEND MEMORIAL HOSPITAL.  SUNPRO WAS RETAINED TO OVERSEE THE CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT, BOTH HAZARDOUS AND NON-HAZARDOUS.  THE CARGO WAS SORTED.  ANY PACKAGES THAT WERE NOT LEAKING WERE REPALLETIZED AND SHIPPED BACK TO THE SHERWIN WILLIAMS DISTRIBUTION CENTER IN EFFINGHAM, IL FOR REWORK.  ALL OPEN CONTAINERS OF NON-HAZARDOUS PAINT WERE POURED IN 55 GAL DRUMS.  SUNPRO IS OVER SEEING THE DISPOSAL OF THE DRUMS.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED INTO A PILE.  SUNPRO IS OVER SEEING THE DISPOSAL OF THE SOIL. EMPTY CONTAINERS, AND TRASH WAS PILED.  SUNPRO WILL ALSO OVER SEE THE DISPOSAL.  SINCE THE ACCIDENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION, WE HAVE NOT FORMULATED A PLAN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.  COPIES OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST ARE NOT AVAILABLE AT THIS TIME TO BE INCLUDED IN THIS REPORT.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING A LEFT TURN FROM HWY 8 ON TO HWY 117 NORTH, IN LEESVILLE, LA.  THE TRACTOR TRAILER ROLLED OVER ON TO THE PASSENGER SIDE AND SPLIT THE CARGO TANK SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 7000 GALLONS OF RED DYED DIESEL WHICH COVERED AN AREA ABOUT THE SIZE OF ONE ACRE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR FATALITIES INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT.

column168: WHILE MAKING DELIVERY, THERE WAS A SMALL LEAK FROM THE EXTERNAL VALVE ASSEMBLY, APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OR LESS, UNLOADING WAS STOPPED, VALVES CLOSED AND TRAILER TAKEN TO REPAIR FACILITY WHERE THE EXTERNAL VALVE WAS DISASSEMBLED AND FOUND TO HAVE A BAD TEFLON GASKET, THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE UNIT RETURNED TO THE CONSIGNEE WHERE DELIVERY WAS COMPLETED.  THE SPILL IN THIS INCIDENT WAS CONTAINED IN A SPILL PAN THAT IS PLACED BENEATH THE PUMP AND ALL VALVES PRIOR TO INITIATING THE UNLOADING PROCESS.

THE JUGS WERE LOADED ON AN OLD PALLET.  A SPLINTER FROM THE PALLET POKED THROUGH THE CARDBOARD AND PUNCTURED ONE OF THE JUGS RESULTING IN A RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.  INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN FOR ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

column168: A SAFETY-KLEEN DRIVER HAD ARRIVED AT SAFETY-KLEEN IN CASEYVILLE, IL WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE GALLON OF WASTE PAINT RELATED MATERIALS HAD BEEN EVACUATED FROM A LEAKING 55 GALLON METAL DRUM ONTO THE TRUCK BED. APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED THE TRAILER BED ONTO A TWO MILE SPAN OF ROADWAY DURING TRANSPORT. THE SPILL RESULTED FROM A PIN HOLE LEAK ON THE 55 GALLON METAL DRUM. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY TEN POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WILL BE DISPOSED AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY LOCATED AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET, DOLTON, IL 60419. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER BLOCKING AND DRUM INSPECTION TECHNIQUES TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS FROM OCCURRING.

column168: A SAFETY-KLEEN DELIVERY TRUCK WAS BEING UNLOADED AT THE FACILITY WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO GALLONS OF WASTE  TETRACHLOROETHYLENE HAD SPILLED ONTO THE CARGO BED OF THE TRUCK. THE SPILL RESULTED FROM A LOOSE LID ON THE CONTAINER. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY TWENTY POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WILL BE DISPOSED AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY LOCATED AT 581 MILLIKEN DRIVE SE IN HEBRON, OHIO. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER BLOCKING AND DRUM CLOSURE TECHNIQUES TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS FROM OCCURRING.

A SAFETY-KLEEN DRIVER WAS EN ROUTE BETWEEN DESTINATIONS WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE 30 GALLON METAL DRUM  CONTAINING 99% WATER AND MERCURY WAS LEAKING ONTO THE TRUCK BED. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF MATERIAL WAS EVACUATED FROM THE CONTAINER AND REMAINED WITHIN THE CARGO COMPARTMENT. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED BY THE DRIVER AND AN OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR, ABSORBED AND CONTAINERIZED THE MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL. THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY TEN POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 2258 RIVER ROAD, LONDON, ONTARIO FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER LOADING AND DRUM INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

A SAFETY-KLEEN DRIVER WAS AT CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES IN CHICAGO, IL WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A PIN HOLE LEAK HAD DEVELOPED ON A 30 GALLON METAL DRUM IN THE REAR OF A TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE-QUARTER GALLON OF MATERIAL WAS EVACUATED FROM THE CONTAINER AND ONE-EIGHT OF ONE GALLON MATERIAL  ESCAPED THE CARGO BED INTO A CONTAINED AREA. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED BY THE DRIVER WHOM ABSORBED AND CONTAINERIZED THE MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL. THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY TWO AND ONE HALF POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS STORED AT THE CLEAN HARBORS LOCATION FOR STORAGE  FOR FUTURE DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER LOADING AND DRUM INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

DRIVER HAD FINISHED UNLOADING THE CARGO TANK AND FAILED TO PROPERLY CLOSE THE VALVES ON THE TRAILER. THE VALVE ON THE TRAILER WAS NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED BEFORE THE DRIVER UNHOOK THE UNLOADING HOSE. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE IN-PLANT CONTAINMENT AND WENT INTO THEIR REPROCESSING SYSTEM. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER PROCEDURES FOR UNLOADING A CARGO TANK.
DRIVER DISCOVERED SPILLAGE, REPORTED TO COMPANY , SPILLED APROX 55 GAL INSIDE TRAILER, ABSORBENT WAS PUT DOWN TO CONTAIN, PRODUCT WAS CLEANED AND OVERPACKED.
DRIVER STATES DURING SAMPLING HE OPENED EXTERNAL & INTERNAL VALVE & REMOVED PLUG AND WHEN HE REMOVED PLUG HE LOST PRODUCT USED SPILL PADS TO CLEAN UP.
TRL LEAKING FROM EXIT VALVE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER. SPILL CLEANED UP WITH SAND & SPILL PADS.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 05:40 (EDT) A FEDEX BOEING 727-200 CRASH LANDED ON APPROACH INTO THE REGIONAL AIRPORT FACILITY AT TALLAHASSEE, FLORIDA. THE FLIGHT NUMBER WAS 1478.   THE AIRCRAFT WAS ARRIVING FROM ITS ORIGIN POINT OF MEMPHIS, TENNESSEE.  THE CREW OF THREE ESCAPED ALIVE WITH MINOR INJURIES.  THE AIRCRAFT WAS COMPLETELY DESTROYED BY FIRE.  CONSEQUENTLY THE ENTIRE FREIGHT LOAD OF THE AIRCRAFT WAS LOST AS WELL.  THERE WERE SEVERAL DANGEROUS GOODS CLASSIFICATIONS EXHIBITED IN THE AIRCRAFT'S FREIGHT LOAD AS WELL THE CLASSES EXHIBITED WERE AS FOLLOWS: 1.4S -EXPLOSIVES, 2.2-NON FLAMMABLE GAS, 7-RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, 8-CORROSIVE, 9-MISCELLANEOUS.  THE LARGEST SINGLE HAZARD AMOUNT EXHIBITED IN THE FREIGHT LOAD WAS 487.1 KG OF CORROSIVE MATERIAL.  THERE WAS AN INDICATION OF SLIGHT CONTAMINATION FROM THE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL THAT WAS DESTROYED IN THE FIRE.  THE ISSUES WITH THE REMAINING CLASSES WERE AS FOLLOWS: 1.4S-NO EXPLOSION OR PERCUSSION HAZARD, CLASS 7-RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL-SLIGHT CONTAMINATION-OTHERWISE ITEMS WERE COMPLETELY DESTROYED, CLASS 8-ITEMS WERE COMPLETELY DESTROYED, CLASS 9-ITEMS WERE COMPLETELY DESTROYED. column168: DURING THE PROCESS OF SETTING RAIL CARS OUT IN BUENA PARK YARD IN LA MIRADA, BNSF TRAIN CREW REPORTED PRODUCT ODOR EMANATING FROM TANK CAR & CREW SAFELY EVACUATED AREA. THE TWO CREW MEMBERS THAT DETECTED THE PRODUCT ODOR WERE TRANSPORTED TO A LOCAL MEDICAL CENTER, EXAMINED FOR AMMONIA EXPOSURE AND RELEASED WITH NO MEDICATIONS PRESCRIBED OR LOST WORK DAYS INCURRED. MEANWHILE, LA COUNTY F.D. HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDERS REPORTED THAT THE PRESSURE PLATE NUTS/BOLTS WERE LOOSE & RECOMMENDED THAT RAIL CAR BE MOVED 1/2 MILE TO CONSIGNEE FACILITY FOR UNLOADING. CONSIGNEE TRANSFERRED PRODUCT TO ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR WITHOUT INCIDENT, DEGASSED/PURGED GATX 78058 & RETURNED IT TO THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER. AFTER GATX 78058 RECEIVED BY SHIPPER, TANK CAR TESTED UNDER PRESSURE WITH NO SOURCE OF LEAK DETECTED. SHIPPER  TO FORWARD TANK CAR TO GATX SHOPS FOR FURTHER INSPECTION & WARRANTED REPAIRS.

TOTE DAMAGE WAS PLUGGED & TAPED WITH TOTE WRAPPED IN ABSORBENT MATERIAL. TOTE WAS RETURNED TO REAR OF TRAILER TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION VIA HIGHWAY.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, THE SIGHT GLASS SEAL BEGAN LEAKING WHICH CAUSED PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND. A SMALL  AMOUNT OF PRODUCT MAY HAVE POSSIBLY ENTERED THE SEWER. A VAC TRUCK WAS CALLED IMMEDIATELY ON SITE TO REMEDIATE THE SEWER SYSTEM.

DRIVER REMOVED DELIVERY HOSE FROM HOSE TRAY AND REMOVED THE CAP ON THE END. A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS IN THE HOSE FROM THE PREVIOUS DELIVERY. THE PRODUCT SPILLED OUT OF THE HOSE ONTO THE GROUND, WHICH WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP. NO SEWERS OR WATERWAYS WERE AFFECTED.
FREIGHT TURNED OVER IN TRAILER AND SMALL AMOUNT SPILLED FROM LIDS.
LOAD SHIFTED AND PALLET FELL PUNCTURING PAIL. SMALL SPILL CLEANED AND OVERPACKED SENT TO DESTINATION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: ON EVENING OF JULY 8 OUR DRIVER WAS ADVISED BY ANOTHER DRIVER THAT MATERIAL WAS LEAKING FROM TRAILER WHILE PARKED AT CITCO TRUCK STOP CLOVERDALE, IN. UPON INVESTIGATION FOUND A 30 GAL FIBRE DRUM HAD TIPPED AND PUNCTURED ON A PALLET. CARRIER WAS NOTIFIED AT 7:40. EMERGENCY RESPONSE WAS PROVIDED BY ECS AND TOTAL CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED BY 7-9-02 AT 0400.

DRIVER NOTICED AQUA COLORED LIQUID OOZING FROM TRAILER FLOOR. REPORTED TO CARRIER. NOTIFIED SHIPPER, CONTACTED EMERGENCY RESPONSE CLEAN UP COMPANY. APPEARS PACKAGING FAILED AS STRETCH WRAP WAS INADEQUATE TO WITHSTAND RIGORS OF HIGHWAY TRAVEL. INADEQUATE BRACING AND CUSTOMERS PUNCTURED OR LIDS CAME LOOSE. SPILL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE AT THE SHELL TRUCK STOP OFF US HIGHWAY 41 IN KENTLAND, INDIANA, THE DRIVER NOTICED FREE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY FOUR QUARTS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED ASPHALT AND SOIL. H.M.H.T.T.C OF GARY, INDIANA RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER. H.M.H.T.T.C PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENTS. THE TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC TERMINAL IN CHICAGO HEIGHTS, ILLINOIS FOR FINAL CLEANUP BY H.M.H.T.T.C. UPON INVESTIGATION, FIVE DAMAGED FIBERBOARD BOXES,EACH CONTAINING FOUR, FIVE GALLON METAL PAILS, WERE DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT NINETEEN PAILS WERE LEAKING. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP CRUSHING THE BOXES. H.M.H.T.T.C. PERSONNEL EMPTIED THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE LEAKING PAILS INTO TWO, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUMS. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WERE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. H.M.H.T.T.C. WILL COORDINATE THE DISPOSITION OF THE PAILS AND THE CLEANUP MATERIALS. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED. ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.

WHILE HANDLING TANK CAR GATX 2033 DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS, CSXT EMPLOYEES OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM  A FITTING ON THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR. THE TANK CAR WAS THEN PLACED IN A LOCATION REMOTE FROM OTHER OPERATIONS AND WHERE IT COULD BE INSPECTED AND/OR REPAIRED. THE SHIPPER OF THE CAR WAS CONTACTED AND INFORMED OF THE SITUATION. THE SHIPPER IN TURN NOTIFIED THE OWNER OF THE TANK CAR (GENERAL AMERICAN TANK CAR (GATX). GATX SENT A TECHNICIAN TO INSPECT THE CAR. THE TECHNICIAN FOUND THAT THE VERTICAL STAND PIPE ON THE "SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY" WAS CRACKED AND ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. THE TECHNICIAN TEMPORARILY SECURED THE LEAKING FITTING UNTIL A NEW PIPE COULD BE OBTAINED AND INSTALLED ON THE CAR. NO PRODUCT LEAKED WHILE THE CAR WAS STATIONARY. ON AUGUST 30 2002 A NEW STAND PIPE WAS INSTALLED AND TESTED. FINDING NO FURTHER LEAKAGE, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF SINGLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT AND FIRE WHICH DESTROYED THE TRACTOR AND DAMAGED THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER. AT THE TIME WERNER ENTERPRISES WAS TRANSPORTING A LOAD OF VARIOUS CONSUMER COMMODITIES INCLUDING, CHEMCLOR. AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT, THE DRIVER WAS HOSPITALIZED WITH INJURIES SUSTAINED FROM THE ACCIDENT AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. CLEAN UP WAS PERFORMED BY U.S. ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES LLC OF JACKSON, MISSISSIPPI. U.S. ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES LLC NEUTRALIZED THE AFFECTED AREA WITH CITRIC ACID. THE UNDAMAGED CARGO IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER. DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED DURING THE CLEAN UP  WILL BE COORDINATED BY U.S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES LLC. ALL STATE, LOCAL AND FEDERAL AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

DRIVER HAD COMPLETED UNLOADING AND WAS DISCONNECTING UNLOADING HOSE. DISCHARGE VALVE (PETROLEUM UNLOADING HEAD) DID NOT COMPLETELY CLOSE AND RELEASED SMALL AMOUNT OF FUEL OIL RESIDUE. DRIVER WAS ABLE TO GET THE VALVE CLOSED.  DRIVER CLEANED UP RELEASE WITH PADS. VALVE WAS INSPECTED AND SEALS REPLACED.

SODIUM HYDROXIDE WAS BEING STORED IN A IN AN MC 307 CARGO TANK THAT WAS BEING USED AS A TEMPORARY STORAGE TANK AND WAS BEING USED IN THE CLEANING OPERATIONS OF A CARGO TANK CLEANING FACILITY. DURING THE CLEANING OF A CARGO TANK, A RETURN LINE WAS INCORRECTLY CONNECTED TO A LINE COMING FROM THE TEMPORARY STORAGE TANK. AS THE CARGO TANK WAS BEING CLEANED, CLEANING SOLUTION WAS BEING PUMPED INTO THE TEMPORARY STORAGE TANK CAUSING IT TO OVERFLOW. AS SOON AS THIS WAS NOTED, THE CLEANING OPERATION WAS SHUT DOWN AND MEASURE TAKEN TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED PRODUCT. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS THOROUGHLY CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. HUMAN ERROR WAS THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL. PERSONNEL INVOLVED WERE AWARE OF PROPER PROCEDURES, BUT THROUGH COMPLACENCY, SIMPLY DID NOT CATCH THE INCORRECT CONNECTION OF THE RETURN LINE.

CARGO TANK WAS BEING LOADED AT THE SHIPPER FACILITY. THE LOADING SYSTEM WAS SET TO SHUT OFF AT 4000 GALLONS. THE AUTOMATIC SHUT OFF FAILED AND APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF PRODUCT OVERFLOWED FROM THE CARGO TANK. SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND WAS CLEANED UP BY MARATHON ASHLAND PERSONNEL. CAUSE OF THE SHIPPER'S LOADING SYSTEM TO FAIL IS NOT KNOWN.
THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS LEAKING WHICH CAUSE THE PRODUCT  TO LEAK OUT OF THE TRAILER.

ALL PRESENT AND FUTURE TRANSPORT OF THESE CHEMICALS HAVE BEEN SUSPENDED.

THE RAILCAR WAS DECONNED AND WEIGHTED. THE WEIGH ON THE RAILCAR WAS 282,600 LBS.***INCIDENT SEVERITY INDEX - 2(5+5+0)(2+0) = 40 ***CAUSE CODE - 422*

CONSIGNEE UNLOADING WITH AIR PRESSURE AND DOME LID WOULD NOT HOLD PRESSURE. DRIVER OPENED DOME LID AND ADJUSTED THE DOME LID GASKET AND SECURED THE DOME LID. CARGO TANK WAS PRESSURIZED AND STILL WOULD NOT SEAL. DRIVER WENT ON TOP OF TRAILER AND WAS HITTING DOME LID FASTENERS WITH A HAMMER IN AN ATTEMPT TO TIGHTEN DOME LID. VAPORS WERE RELEASED FROM VAPOR RECOVERY LINE AND CONTAMINATED DRIVERS LEFT UPPER ARM. UNLOADING WAS DISCONTINUED. DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE EMERGENCY SHOWER AND REFUSED MEDICAL TREATMENT.  DRIVER WAS RELEASED FROM LOAD BY MOTOR CARRIER AND DROPPED CARGO TANK TRAILER AT CONSIGNEE AND BOBTAILED HOME. DRIVER FAILED TO WEAR COMPLETE SET OF PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AS REQUIRED BY MOTOR CARRIER AND CONSIGNEE. REPAIR SERVICE WAS SENT TO REPLACE DOME LID GASKET AND SHIPMENT WAS OFF LOADED THE FOLLOWING DAY WITH OUT FURTHER INCIDENT VAPOR RECOVERY VALVE WAS INSPECTED WITH NO DEFECT DISCOVERED. IT IS BELIEVED THAT DRIVER KNOCKED OFF VAPOR CAP AND ACCIDENTALLY OPENED VAPOR VALVE WHILE WORKING ON DOME LID. DRIVER FAILED TO FOLLOW OPERATING PROCEDURES AND PPE REQUIREMENTS. CONTRACT WAS CANCELLED.

CONSIGNEE BEGAN AIR UNLOADING AND MALE FITTING ON EXTERNAL VALVE BEGAN LEAKING. RELEASED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN A BUCKET. MALE FITTING WAS TIGHTENED AND UNLOADING CONTINUED WITH OUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

CONTACTED HULCHER SERVICES, INC., OF HOUSTON, TEXAS TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP. HULCHER SERVICES PERSONNEL USED ABSORBENTS TO REMOVE THE NEUTRALIZED FREE PRODUCT FROM THE ASPHALT SERVICE. WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM OF WASTE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

APPROXIMATELY ONE POUND OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT, WHICH CAUSED THE VALVE ON TOP OF THE CYLINDER TO BECOME LOOSE. column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE LOADING, FOUR WET CARTONS EACH CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC PAILS WERE DISCOVERED ON THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE PAIL WAS DAMAGED AND THE OTHER FIFTEEN PAILS WERE AFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE PAIL WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A FORKLIFT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG, A BROOM AND A SHOVEL. THE CLEANUP SUITS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, BROOM AND SHOVEL WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE FOUR WET CARTONS AND DAMAGED PAIL WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. ALL THREE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE FIFTEEN AFFECTED PAILS WERE CLEANED OFF, REPACKAGED AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE LOADING, ONE WET FIBERBOARD CARTON CONTAINING SIX, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE JUG WAS LEAKING AND THE OTHER FIVE WERE AFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED INTO THE TRAILER. THE DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINED WAS DUE TO PUNCTURE BY OTHER FREIGHT DURING LOADING. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENTS, PADS, GLOVES, A DUSTPAN AND A BROOM. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, ABSORBENTS, PADS, WET CARTON AND LEAKING JUG WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. column168: DURING TRANSPORTATION, A BIG SCREEN TELEVISION THAT WAS LOADED ON TOP OF THE TOTE CONTAINING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIFTED.  THE CORNER OF THE TELEVISION'S SHIPPING CONTAINER PRESSED AGAINST AND INDENTED THE PLASTIC PORTION OF THE TOTE THROUGH THE METAL CAGE THAT SURROUNDED IT.  THIS REDUCTION IN CONTAINER SIZE PRESSURIZED THE INSIDE OF THE TOTE AND RAISED THE FLUID LEVEL.  THE FLUID BEGAN TO LEAK FROM THE SCREW TYPE LID ON THE TOTE.  WHEN THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR TRAILER STOPPED AND CHECKED HIS LOAD, HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID COMING OUT OF THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER THEN IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED WATKINS MOTOR LINES WHO INTURN NOTIFIED A CONTRACTED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE COMPANY TO TAKE CARE OF THE INCIDENT.  THE RESPONSE COMPANY CLEANED UP THE ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT THAT WAS RELEASED, AND SECURED THE TELEVISION WITH 2X4 BOARDS TO PREVENT IT FROM SHIFTING AGAIN.  THE RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS CONFINED TO THE TRAILER AND A ONE FOOT SQUARE SECTION OF GRAVEL.  THE CONTAMINATED GRAVEL WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE.

DRIVERS FOUND A SLIGHT LEAK OF A SUBSTANCE FROM THE REAR OF TRAILER.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP CREW WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE FOR CLEANUP.  ONE 55 GALLON DRUM OF ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, NOS (CHROMIC SULFATE), 9, UN3082, PGIII, WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AND HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 20 TO 25 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CREW INSPECTED THE DRUM AND FOUND A SMALL STRESS CRACK THAT RADIATED OUT 1/2 INCH FROM THE LIP OF THE DRUM.  THERE WERE NO SCRAPES, PUNCTURE OR ANY OTHER CAUSE FOR THE CRACK IN THE DRUM OTHER THAN IT BEING A STRESS CRACK.  THE DRUM WAS A BLACK RECONDITIONED DRUM WITH AN OPEN HEAD.  THE DRUM WAS COMPLETELY UNMARKED WITHOUT ANY DRUM RECONDITION MARKINGS.  A TOTAL OF FOUR 55-GALLON DRUMS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL, GRAVEL, ABSORBENT AND PPE WAS GENERATED AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF.  THE 55 GALLON DRUM OF PRODUCT WAS OVERPACKED INTO AN 85 GALLON DRUM AND WAS SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.

THERE WAS ABOUT 12 DRUMS ON THE LEFT SIDE OF TRAILER, HE SAID HIS SKID OF PAILS WERE ON TOP OF DRUMS. column168: SODIUM HYDROXIDE WAS BEING STORED IN A IN AN MC 307 CARGO TANK THAT WAS BEING USED AS A TEMPORARY STORAGE TANK AND WAS BEING USED IN THE CLEANING OPERATIONS OF A CARGO TANK CLEANING FACILITY. DURING  THE CLEANING OF A CARGO TANK A RETURN LINE WAS INCORRECTLY CONNECTED TO A LINE COMING FROM THE TEMPORARY STORAGE TANK. AS THE CARGO TANK WAS BEING CLEANED, CLEANING SOLUTION WAS BEING PUMPED INTO THE TEMPORARY STORAGE TANK CAUSING IT TO OVERFLOW. AS SOON AS THIS WAS NOTED, THE CLEANING OPERATION WAS SHUT DOWN, AND MEASURE TAKEN TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED PRODUCT. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS THOROUGHLY CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF HUMAN ERROR WAS THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL. PERSONNEL INVOLVED WERE AWARE OF PROPER PROCEDURES, BUT THROUGH COMPLACENCY, SIMPLY DID NOT CATCH THE INCORRECT CONNECTION OF THE RETURN LINE.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: ON FRIDAY, JULY 12, 2002, OUR DRIVER RETURNED TO OUR TERMINAL AT 400 WEST REGENT STREET, INDIANAPOLIS, IN FROM OUR CINCINNATI TERMINAL WITH A MIXED LOAD OF MATERIALS, INCLUDING THE CONTAINERS SPECIFIED IN THIS REPORT. UPON INSPECTING THE LOAD UPON DELIVERY, AT APPROXIMATELY 0330, JULY 13, THERE WAS NO NOTATION OF A RELEASE. UPON RETURNING TO DUTY AT 1930, JULY 14, THE DRIVER NOTICED A STAIN ON THE CONCRETE BELOW THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. UPON INVESTIGATING, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE OF THE DRUMS FROM THE SHIPMENT 71102 HAD LOST ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER, WHICH SUBSEQUENTLY RAN OUT TO THE CONCRETE PAD BELOW , AND EVAPORATED. THE RELEASE WAS REPORTED TO THE DISPATCHER AT THAT  TIME. BECAUSE THERE WAS NO IMMEDIATE HAZARD, NO REPORT WAS MADE TO THE ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENT. UPON START OF BUSINESS MONDAY, JULY 15, 0800. THE RELEASE WAS REPORTED TO THE ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENT, AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE RELEASE CONSTITUTED A REPORTABLE QUANTITY, AND IT WAS SUBSEQUENTLY REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER UNDER INCIDENT REPORT 616649. FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY AN UNKNOWN OBJECT, AT AN UNDETERMINED TIME. THE ACTUAL HOLE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1MM IN DIAMETER. ALL OF THE RELEASED MATERIAL HAD EVAPORATED FROM THE CONCRETE PAD, LEAVING ONLY NON VOLATILE RESIDUE, WHICH WAS CLEANED UP, AND DISPOSED OF AS HAZARDOUS WASTE WITH COMPATIBLE MATERIALS.

ARRIVED AT TERMINAL AROUND 3:00 AM ON 07/29/2002. WAS ADVISED BY AN EMPLOYEE OF OUR GUARD SERVICE THAT THERE WAS A LEAK AROUND ONE OF OUR TRAILERS DROPPED IN A DOOR AT THE DOCK. I CHECKED THE LEAKAGE AROUND THE TRAILER & THEN WENT TO OPEN THE DOOR TO IDENTIFY THE PRODUCT, NOTICED A DRUM ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING DUE TO FORK DAMAGED. DRUM HAD BEEN STRUCK WITH A FORKLIFT. DUE TO THE VIBRATION OF THE ROAD DURING LINEHAUL TO OUR TERMINAL THE DRUM STARTED LEAKING THE CORROSIVE PRODUCT.
IT LOOKS LIKE THE CARTON GOT PUNCTURED BY OTHER FREIGHT.
WHEN THEY ARRIVED, VAPOR WAS BEING RELEASED FROM THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER. BY THE TIME CLEAN HARBORS RESPONDED, ALMOST ALL MATERIAL HAD BEEN RELEASED.

column168: CARRIER'S VEHICLE WAS IN A TRUCK STOP WHEN THE DRIVER OBSERVED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER IN THE AREA OF ITS LANDING GEAR. TRUCK STOP PERSONNEL DIRECTED THE DRIVER TO A REMOTE AREA OF THE PARKING LOT. THEY PROVIDE A PAIL AND SOME ABSORBENT MATERIAL. DRIVER USED THESE TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE. THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS DETERMINED TO BE NEAR THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. IN ORDER TO ACCESS AND IDENTIFY THE LEAKER, IT WOULD BE NECESSARY TO UNLOAD MUCH OF THE LOAD IN THE TRAILER. CARRIER'S HAZMAT SPECIALIST CONTACTED THE DISPATCHER FOR THE AREA. THE DISPATCHER MADE AVAILABLE ANOTHER DRIVER AND EMPTY VEHICLE. ON ARRIVAL, THE DRIVERS MOVED MUCH OF THE FREIGHT INTO THE OTHER TRAILER. THEY WERE THEN ABLE TO ACCESS THE REST OF THE LOAD AND TENTATIVELY IDENTIFY THE LEAKING PACKAGE. THERE WAS A PALLET CONTAINING FOUR PLASTIC  DRUMS OF DIFFERENT PRODUCTS, ALL CORROSIVES. ONE OF THE DRUMS APPEARED TO BE PARTIALLY COLLAPSED, AS IF IT WERE UNDER A VACUUM. THERE WAS LIQUID RADIATING AWAY FROM THAT DRUM. AT THAT POINT, THE HAZMAT SPECIALIST INSTRUCTED THE DRIVERS TO EXIT THE TRAILER. THE SPECIALIST ARRANGED FOR A CONTRACTOR TO BE SENT TO THE SITE AND TO TAKE OVER THE INCIDENT MITIGATION. AFTER ARRIVAL AND ASSESSMENT BY THE CONTRACTOR, THEY AND THE TWO DRIVERS UNLOADED ENOUGH OF THE REST OF THE TRAILER TO ALLOW THEM TO REMOVE THE LEAKING DRUM. IT WAS FOUND TO HAVE A HOLE IN ITS BOTTOM, CAUSED BY A PROTRUDING NAIL IN THE SHIPPER'S PALLET. THE CONTRACTOR'S PERSONNEL PLACED THE DRUM UPSIDE DOWN INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THEY PUT ABSORBENTS ONTO THE REMAINING LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. MOST OF THE FREIGHT WAS PUT ONTO THE SECOND TRAILER. WHEN THE WORK WAS COMPLETED, BOTH OF THE CARRIER'S VEHICLES CONTINUED TO THE CARRIER'S CHICAGO, III FACILITY.

TWO CARTONS WERE OBSERVED TO BE LEAKING FROM A TEAR IN THE OUTER FIBER BOX AND THROUGH TO THE INNER LINING WHEN INVESTIGATED AT THE CONSIGNEE'S DOCK. THE CONTAINER'S WERE APPARENTLY TORN DURING THE LOADING OR UNLOADING PROCESS.  APPROXIMATELY ONE POUND OF PRODUCT SPILLED FROM A TEAR IN THE BAG INTO THE TRAILER.  THE CARTONS WERE PLACED IN A PLASTIC AND INTO THE TRAILER.  THE CARTONS WERE PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG AND INTO A FIBER DRUM. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED INTO THE PLASTIC BAG.  THE DRUM WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS ASSIGNED TO DRIVE A MACK TRUCK, HOWEVER, TOOK IT UPON HIMSELF TO GET A NEW FREIGHTLINER INSTEAD.  AS A RESULT, THE DRIVER WAS IN AN UNFAMILIAR TRUCK WITH A DIFFERENT TRANSMISSION.  THIS WAS THE MAIN CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN THE INCIDENT.  THE DRIVER WAS IN ROUTE TO MAKE A DELIVERY TO A TEXACO STATION ON POWERS FERRY ROAD IN MARIETTA, GA.  HE HAD COME TO A STOP AT THE TRAFFIC LIGHT AT THE INTERSECTION OF POWERS FERRY RD. AND WINDY HILL RD.  UPON THE TRAFFIC LIGHT CHANGING, HE BEGAN TO ACCELERATE THROUGH THE INTERSECTION WHILE MAKING A LEFT HAND TURN.  THE TRUCK WAS IN A LEFT TURN WHILE AT THE SAME TIME GOING UP A SIGNIFICANT GRADE OF ROAD. DURING THE PROGRESSION THROUGH THE INTERSECTION, THE DRIVER WAS HAVING TROUBLE GETTING THE UNIT TO GO INTO GEAR WHILE SHIFTING.  AS A RESULT, THE DRIVER BECAME FRUSTRATED AND DECIDED TO STOP THE UNIT IN ORDER TO RESTART THE SHIFT PATTERN FOR THE TRANSMISSION.  DURING THIS SEQUENCE OF EVENTS, THE PRODUCT IN THE TANKER SHIFTED FORWARD DUE TO THE SUDDEN STOP.  AS A RESULT OF THE SUDDEN STOP, THE ANGLE AT WHICH THE UNIT POSITIONED, AND THE SLOPE OF THE INTERSECTION, THE FRONT OF THE TANKER BEGAN TO ROLLOVER TOWARDS THE RIGHT HAND SIDE.  ACCORDING TO AN EYEWITNESS, THE TRUCK WAS ONLY TRAVELING 5-10 MILES AN HOUR BEFORE IT BEGAN TO COME TO A STOP AND ROLLOVER.

THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE SHIPMENT WITH A NOTATION OF THE CONDITION AND ASSISTED THE DRIVER TO CLEAN UP THE TRAILER FLOOR.

column168: A SHIPMENT OF EMPTY PORTABLE TANKS HAD BEEN SHIPPED WITHOUT CLOSURE CAPS OVER THE DISCHARGE PORTS.  THEY HAD BEEN DOUBLE STACKED AND LOADED SIDEWAYS IN THE CARRIER'S TRAILER.  DURING UNLOADING, THE DISCHARGE VALVE HANDLE OF ONE TANK BRUSHED AGAINST THE TRAILER WALL.  THE VALVE OPENED, ALLOWING SPILLAGE OF ABOUT A GALLON OF PRODUCTS RESIDUE.  THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE SHIPMENT GIVING A CLEAR RECEIPT, AND ASSISTED THE DRIVER IN CLEANING THE SPILLAGE FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR.

PRIOR TO LOADING THIS TOTE IN THE NALCO DELIVERY TRAILER, APPROXIMATELY 10 OUNCES OF PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF THE TOTE FROM THE BOTTOM.  TOTE IS PLASTIC, COMPLETELY SURROUNDED BY METAL OUTER SHELL.  UPON INSPECTION, NO VISIBLE DAMAGE NOR POINT OF LEAK WAS DETERMINED.  TOTE WAS PLACED ON A CARDBOARD SHEET AND SEGREGATED AT THE END OF THE DOCK AWAY FROM PERSONNEL. ANNOUNCEMENT OVER SERVICE CENTER PUBLIC ADDRESS SYSTEM WAS MADE TO ADVISE ALL PERSONNEL OF INCIDENT.  CWX SAFETY SUPERVISOR WAS IMMEDIATELY CALLED TO REPORT INCIDENT.  CONSIGNEE'S 24 HOUR EMERGENCY NUMBER WAS CALLED. CONSIGNEE WAS ALSO CALLED DIRECTLY AS THEY ARE A REGULAR CWX CUSTOMER AND LOCATED LESS THAN A MILE AWAY.  CONSIGNEE DISPATCHED A SAFETY EXPERT TO EVALUATE SITUATION.  NALCO REPRESENTATIVE COULD NOT LOCATE POINT OF LEAK AND DETERMINED THAT THE TOTE WAS NO LONGER LEAKING AND SAFE TO TRANSPORT. NALCO REPRESENTATIVE CLEANED UP WHAT HAD SPILLED ON CWX DOCK AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.

column168: ON JULY 25TH, 2002 A STAMPEDE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO UNLOAD 6300 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE AT RIP GRIFFIN TRUCK CENTER IN PRESCOTT, AR.  BASED ON READINGS PRIOR TO UNLOADING, THE UNDERGROUND TANK HAD MORE THAN ENOUGH CAPACITY TO HOLD THE 6300 GALLONS.  UPON UNLOADING, IT BECAME APPARENT THAT THE LOAD WAS UNLOADING VERY SLOWLY. AN INSURANCE CLAIM WAS PLACED WITH FEDERATED INSURANCE COMPANY.

ONE 3 POUND PACKAGE OF SODIUM SELENITE WAS DROPPED AND RIPPED OPEN BY A FORKLIFT FORKS ON THE DOCK AT THE CF TERMINAL IN INDIANAPOLIS, INDIANA. JACK CARTER OF CF CONTACTED BRANDON GRIFFITH OF EMI AND REQUESTED SOME GUIDANCE.  THERE WAS LESS THAN ONE OUNCE OF PRODUCT SPILLED ON THE DOCK CONCRETE FLOOR,  IT WAS AGREED TO LET THE CF PERSONNEL SWEEP THE MATERIAL INTO A CONTAINER FOR TEMPORARY STORAGE.  IT WAS UNKNOWN AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT WHETHER OR NOT THE PACKAGE AND CLEANUP PRODUCT WOULD BE SENT ON TO ITS DESTINATION OR SENT FOR DISPOSAL.  ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS WAS TO USE BETTER PRECAUTION WHILE UNLOADING PACKAGES WITH THE FORKLIFT.

ON JULY 4, 2002 AROUND 6:00P.M. A KELLERSTRASS DRIVER KELLY REYNOLDS WAS UNLOADING FROM A CARGO TANK INTO A STORAGE TANK AT CENTERFIRE 66 GAS STATION IN PIPEDALE, WYOMING. A UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF DIESEL FUEL OF 20 GALLONS WAS SPILLED OUT THE VENT PIPE OF THE STORAGE TANK. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE VALVES ON THE CARGO TANK AND PROCEEDED TO START CLEAN UP WITH ULTRA-SORB AND ABSORB PADS. MY DRIVER CLEANED UP THE SPILL WITH THE SPILL KIT AND THEN TALKING WITH THE EMPLOYEES AND THE STATION THERE WERE SATISFIED AND THE DRIVER LEFT. I RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM THE DRIVER STATING THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND HE WAS LEAVING THE STATION. AFTER THE DRIVER HAD LEFT THE STATION A EMPLOYEE OF THE STATION PROCEEDED TO WASH THE STATION DOWN WITH A WATER HOSE BRINGING THE DIESEL BACK OUT OF THE ASPHALT AND MAKING THE DIESEL RISE BACK TO THE TOP OF THE ASPHALT. I RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM WES JOHNSTON-PINEDALES FIRE MARSHALL STATING THE STATION WAS BEING EVACUATED DUE TO THE FUEL SPILL AND THE STRONG SMELL OF PRODUCT AND INFORMED ME THAT WE NEEDED TO GET THE PARKING LOT CLEANED UP. WE SENT ANOTHER EMPLOYEE OUT OF OGDEN, UT TO ASSIST IN THE CLEAN-UP. WE THEN SWEPT UP THE PARKING LOT WITH ULTRA-SORB AND THEN APPLIED MORE ULTRA-SORB TO FINISH UP THE PARKING LOT. THE STATION WAS COMPLETELY CLEANED UP BY 2:30A.M. AND THE PADS AND ULTRA-SORB WERE HAULED OFF.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE LOADING AT THE WILSON FACILITY, ON 1801 BLOUNT ROAD, TWO, SIXTY GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS WERE PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT. APPROXIMATELY FIFTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. WILSON TRUCKING PERSONNEL PLACED ABSORBENTS AND DUNNAGE DOWN TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT BUT IT WAS RAINING HEAVILY AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL. WILSON TRUCKING CONTACTED CLIFF BERRY, INC. OF FORT LAUDERDALE, FLORIDA TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. THE POMPANO BEACH FIRE AND RESCUE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED AND ON THE SCENE. CLIFF BERRY, INC. PLACED ADDITIONAL OIL DRY AND A NEUTRALIZER DOWN ON THE FREE PRODUCT TO HELP FURTHER CONTAIN THE SPILL. CLIFF BERRY, INC. PLACED THE TWO DAMAGED DRUMS WITH REMAINING PRODUCT INTO TWO, EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS. CLIFF BERRY, INC. ALSO GENERATED TWO DRUMS OF LIQUID WASTE CONSISTING OF RAIN WATER AND FREE PRODUCT WHICH HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE DRUMS. THE IMPACTED ABSORBENTS, OIL DRY AND DUNNAGE WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM AND 175 POUNDS WORTH OF RECOVERY BAGS. CLIFF BERRY, INC. WILL TRANSPORT THE RECOVERY BAGS TO WHEELABRATOR IN FORT LAUDERDALE, FLORIDA FOR DISPOSITION VIA INCINERATION. THE FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM OF IMPACTED ABSORBENTS, OIL DRY AND DUNNAGE WILL GO TO RINKER IN MIAMI, FLORIDA FOR DISPOSAL VIA INCINERATION. THE TWO DRUMS OF LIQUID AND THE TWO DRUMS CONTAINING THE DAMAGED DRUMS WILL GO TO US LIQUIDS IN TAMPA, FLORIDA FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.

column168: DRIVER MARK HELMSMAN WAS UNLOADING A TRAILER WHEN HE ENTERED THE TRAILER AND PUNCTURED A 55 GALLON DRUM OF PAINT. THE PUNCTURED DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND HELD FOR DISPOSITION.

THE DRIVER WENT TO MAUI TOY FOR A DELIVERY.  MAUI TOY IS LOCATED AT 1275 CRESCENT STREET, YOUNGSTOWN, OH.  THE FREIGHT WAS UNLOADED TO MAUI TOY AND THAT IS WHEN THE PEOPLE FROM MAUI TOY DISCOVERED THE LEAK.  UPON THAT THE DRIVER BRYANT SHELTON CALLED DAVE OUR DISPATCHER THIS WAS AT 2:00 PM.  DAVE GOT OFF THE PHONE WITH THE BRYANT AND CALLED THE CONSIGNEE AND TALKED TO CHRISTINE PIZZULO PLANT MANAGER.  DAVE ASKED WHAT WAS LEAKING AND HOW BAD WAS THE LEAK.  SHE STATED THAT SHE DID NOT KNOW HOW BAD THE LEAK WAS BUT IS DRIPPING OUT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER AND SOME LIQUID WAS ON THE FLOOR.  AT THAT TIME DAVE CHECKED THE BILLS TO SEE WHAT WAS ON THE TRAILER AND FOUND OUT IS WAS CORROSIVE LIQUIDS.  HE AND CHRISTINE PIZZULO TALKED TO MAKE SURE IT WAS THE DRUMS LEAKING.  AT THAT TIME SHE SAID THAT SHE WAS CONCERNED ABOUT THE DRUMS LEAKING.  DAVE INSTRUCTED HER TO CALL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HE WOULD GET BACK WITH HER.  DAVE CALLED ME RIGHT AWAY AND I GAVE THE PHONE TO JOHN FERENCZI.  JOHN AND MYSELF WENT OUT TO THE SPILL SITE THIS WAS AT 2:30 PM.  WE ARRIVED AT THE SPILL SITE AT 4:15 PM.  MAHONING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM WAS ALREADY ON SITE ALONG WITH YOUNGSTOWN FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION OF OHIO.  WE TALKED TO THE YOUNGSTOWN FIRE DEPARTMENT CAPT RUSSO.  HE HAD THE MSDS PAPER WORK THAT WAS FAXED TO HIM.  CAPTAIN RUSSO TOLD ME THAT THE SCENE WAS CONTAINED.  WHICH THERE WAS NO LEAKING INTO THE WATER SYSTEM.  HE HAD OIL DRY AROUND THE SPILL.  I WENT LOOKING FOR THE CHIEF OF THE HAZ-MAT RESCUE TEAM.  I FOUND CHIEF CLYDE MACKENZIE AND HE TOLD ME AT THIS POINT WE CANNOT GET A HOLD OF THE CONSIGNEE TO SEE WHAT THEY USED THE MATERIAL FOR.  HE WAS ASKING THE CONSIGNEE TO SEE HOW HAZARDOUS THE LIQUID WAS AND WHAT PROTECTION THEY USE FOR THIS LIQUID.  THEN WE HAD TO WAIT UNTIL A DECISION WAS MADE ABOUT THE LIQUID.  WHILE WE HAD TO WAIT, I GOT A STATEMENT FROM THE DRIVER BRYANT SHELTON.  (SEE ATTACHED STATEMENT, WHICH HE WROTE UP) I CONTACTED CHIEF MACKENZIE AGAIN AND IT WAS DECIDED THAT THEY WERE NOT GOING TO TAKE ANY CHANCES SO THEY PUT ON THEIR SPACE SUITS THIS WAS AT ABOUT 5:15 PM.  THEY ENTERED THE DOCK AREA AND PROCEEDED TO ENTER THE TRAILER.  THEY PROCEEDED TO PUT THE LEAKING DRUM INTO A OVER PACK CONTAINER BUT THEY LEFT THE LID OFF BECAUSE OF THE VACUUM OF THE DRUM MADE IT TO TALL PER CHIEF MACKENZIE ALSO THEY SAW NO DAMAGE THAT COULD HAVE OCCURRED FROM MID-STATES EXPRESS. THEY WERE IN THE TRAILER ABOUT 30 MINS.  AT THAT POINT THE RAIN CAME DOWN SO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ADDED MORE OIL DRY BUT BECAUSE OF THE RAIN SOME OF THE CHEMICAL WENT DOWN THE DRAIN.  THEY THEN HAD TO FLUSH THE DRAIN.  IT TOOK 500 GALLONS OF WATER TO FLUSH THE DRAIN.  AT 6:00 PM.  I CALLED THE SUN PRO THE HAZ-MAT CLEAN UP COMPANY AND TALKED TO DUSTIN DULEBOHM.  I TOLD HIM OF THE SPILL AND FAXED HIM THE MSDS PAPERS.  AFTER HE GOT INFORMATION ON OUR COMPANY HE WOULD HAVE HIS TEAM ASSEMBLED AND BE OUT IN AN HOUR.  AT 6:30 AFTER TALKING TO BOTH CAPTAIN AND CHIEF AND LE

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE ZONE 6 ATO CSM JEFF RODRIGUEZ AT 1825 ADVISING THEY HAD FOUND SOME HIDDEN DG DURING A ROUTINE CTX SCREENING.  HE STATED IT WAS A LARGE BOX CONTAINING A LAWN EDGER THAT HAD GAS IN THE TANK.  JEFF STATED THE AA AGENT, IRENE HAWORTH, RECOGNIZED THE BOX AS A TRIGGER AND ASKED WHAT'S INSIDE.  THE PASSENGER REPLIED IT WAS A NEW LAWN EDGER.  THE AGENT SPECIFICALLY ASKED IF THERE WAS GAS IN THE TANK AND THE PASSENGER SAID NO.  THE AGENT THEN SENT THE PASSENGER AND LUGGAGE TO THE CTX MACHINE FOR FURTHER SCREENING.  THE TSA SUPERVISOR, ANITA SIRRS SAW THE EDGER AND SMELLED GASOLINE, WHICH HAD SPILLED INTO THE PACKING PAPER INSIDE THE BOX AS IT WAS TILTED TO LOAD INTO CTX.  THE FUEL COULD BE SEEN WHEN THE CAP WAS REMOVED FROM THE TANK.  THE LAWN EDGER WAS CONFISCATED AND I SPOKE WITH THE PASSENGER.  SHE STATED SHE BOUGHT THE LAWN EDGER TODAY AT A PAWNSHOP AND DID NOT KNOW THERE WAS GAS IN THE TANK.  IT WAS ABOUT ONE EIGHTH FULL.  SHE WAS GIVEN A DOT THESE FLY..THESE MAY NOT BROCHURE, SHOWN THE LAMINATED PORTABLE KIOSK, AND HAD THE SECTION OF THE 5 IN 1 SIGN POSTED ON THE FRONT OF THE COUNTER POINTED OUT TO HER.  SHE WAS ALSO VERBALLY EDUCATED RE CARRIAGE OF UNDECLARED DG ON PASSENGER AIRCRAFT.

WHILE LOADING OUTBOUND FLIGHT 1682 TO TPA THE GROUND CREW NOTICED BLEACH LIKE ODOR FROM A BAG.  THE BAG WAS ISOLATED AND THE EC WAS CALLED.  AFTER FURTHER INSPECTION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT TPA PAX JONES WAS TRANSPORTING A 6 OZ TUPPERWARE CONTAINER IN A PLASTIC BAG WHICH HAD A LIQUID CONSISTENT WITH THE ODOR OF BLEACH.  PAX WAS CONTACTED AND ASKED TO IDENTIFY SUBSTANCE.  PAX ID AS BLEACH.  A 2 X 4 INCH AREA OF THE A2 CARGO COMPARTMENT WAS CONTAMINATED WITH BLEACH.  PAX JONES IDENTIFIED THE SUBSTANCE AS BLEACH THAT WAS CONSISTENT WITH THE ODOR AND PHYSICAL PROPERTIES.  SPILL WAS CLEANED.  AC MNTC WAS NOTIFIED AND INSPECTED THE AREA.  AC MNTC MADE A LOG BOOK ENTRY AND CLEARED THE AIRCRAFT.

DEAN COOPER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, REPORTED CONTAINER KLTU 112704, PLACARDED CORROSIVE, WAS NOTED LEAKING.  APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF MATERIAL LEAKED FROM UNDERNEATH THE CONTAINER AND ONTO THE PAVEMENT BELOW.  TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL WAS EN ROUTE TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL WITH THE REWORK OF THE LADING TO COMMENCE THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  THE CONTAINER WAS PLACED ON TO PLASTIC TO SECURE ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKING PRODUCT OVER NIGHT.  UPON OPENING THE DOORS, IT WAS NOTED THE LADING CONSISTED OF METAL 55 GALLON OPEN HEAD DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED THROUGHOUT THE CONTAINER. THE DRUMS DID NOT HAVE EVERY OTHER ROW RISERED TO OFF SET THE CLOSURE RINGS, ALLOWING THE DRUMS TO TILT AGAINST EACH OTHER.  WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS, LOCATED ONE DRUM THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE NOTED ON THE BOTTOM CHIME, INDICATING THE CHIME HAD FAILED.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND SECURED.  ESTIMATED 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST FROM THIS DRUM.  18 ADDITIONAL DRUMS WERE ALSO NOTED WEEPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME.  NO DAMAGE WAS NOTED TO THE CHIMES ON THE ADDITIONAL DRUMS.  ALL WERE PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT.  THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE AND RELEASED FOR RETURN TO K LINE.  THE LADING, INCLUDING THE SALVAGE DRUMS, WAS LOADED INTO A NEW CONTAINER, KKFU 109588, FOR RETURN TO THE MANUFACTURER PER THEIR REQUEST.

THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND PLACED ON PLASTIC.  TRAILER WAS NOT LEAKING ON JULY 14, 2002.  NAPZ DRAYAGE DELIVERED THE TRAILER TO DUPONT ON JULY 15, 2002.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY TWO 55 GALLON BARRELS OF A PAINT ACTIVATOR THAT HAD RUBBED TOGETHER DURING TRANSIT AND RUBBED HOLES INTO BOTH BARRELS.  ACCORDING TO THE DOCK MANAGER AT DUPONT THERE WAS SIX GALLONS MISSING FROM ONE BARREL AND TWO GALLONS MISING FROM THE OTHER.  THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS IMPROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING.

E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 17266-CF PERSONNEL WERE UNLOADING INTERMODAL CONTAINER #BMDZ3560 AND DISCOVERED THAT A CARDBOARD CARTON HAD BEEN CRUSHED AND NOTICED LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE CARTON CONTAINED TWO 1-GALLON METAL CONTAINERS OF XYLENE SOLUTION (FLAMMABLE LIQUID). UPON INSPECTING THE METAL CONTAINERS, IT WAS NOTED THAT ONE OF THEM HAD BEEN CRUSHED AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF PRODUCT. CF PERSONNEL USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CLEANUP THE IMPACTED AREA OF THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE DAMAGED CONTAINER AND THE CLEANUP MATERIAL WERE PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM, SEALED, AND SECURED PENDING DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS. IT WAS NOTED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING (HEAVY FREIGHT WAS STACKED ON TOP OF CARTON).  ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT CONTACTED MIKE KILLOUGH (CF REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER) AND NOTIFIED HIM OF THE INCIDENT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RELATED TO THIS INCIDENT.

E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 17320: CF DOCK PERSONNEL DISCOVERED CARTON LEAKING ON DOCK FLOOR AND NOTIFIED DOCK SUPERVISOR. IN REVIEW SHIPPING  DOCUMENTS, THE CARTON WAS IDENTIFIED AS CONTAINING QUART BOTTLES (4) OF CHLOROFORM, 6.1 (INHALATION HAZARD), UN1888, PG III.  A LARGE INDUSTRIAL FAN WAS SET UP TO BLOW ANY VAPORS AWAY FROM THE DOCK AND ISOLATED THE AREA. CF PERSONNEL THEN NOTIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT OF THE RELEASE. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT DISPATCHED A RESPONSE TEAM FROM SPILL RECOVERY OF INDIANA (SROI) TO THE INCIDENT SITE. UPON ARRIVAL SROI INSPECTED THE CARTON AND FOUND THAT IT HAD BEEN CRUSHED AND THAT ONE OF THE QUART BOTTLES HAD ALSO BEEN CRUSHED AND RELEASED ITS CONTENTS (1 QUART). UPON THE REQUEST OF CF PERSONNEL THE ENTIRE CARTON WAS PLACED IN A DRUM LINER AND THEN PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THE DOCK FLOOR WAS THEN CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THIS MATERIAL WAS ALSO PLACED IN THE OVERPACK DRUM. THE DRUM WAS SEALED AND LEFT ON SITE AS PER CF'S REQUEST. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT CONTACTED TIM MURPHY (CF REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER)  AND NOTIFIED HIM OF THE INCIDENT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RELATED TO THIS INCIDENT.

E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 17282 CF STAFF CLEANED UP THE SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE AND PLACED THE DRUM IN AN OVERPACK DRUM. THE SPILLAGE WAS ALSO PLACED INSIDE THE OVERPACK DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS THEN SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER FOR REPACKAGING.

column168: TOBY TREVETT, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT, ADVISED OF A REPORTEDLY LEAKING TANKCAR. THE CAR WAS LOCATED AT THE EAST END OF THE AVONDALE YARD ON TRACK 85. TREVETT ADVISED THAT THE CAR WAS IN THE STORAGE AREA OF THE YARD AND TRAIN TRAFFIC HAD BEEN STOPPED FOR INBOUND AND OUTBOUND TRAINS. MR. TREVETT REPORTED A MINOR VAPOR RELEASE COMING FROM THE TOP MANWAY COVER, HOWEVER DUE TO WIND CONDITIONS THE PRODUCT WAS DISSIPATING QUICKLY. THE INCIDENT WAS DISCOVERED WHEN A PASSING TRAIN CREW SUFFERED MINOR EYE IRRITATIONS, MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NOT REQUESTED. ALL NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE. JULIAN LOPEZ, AIR PRODUCTS 610-481-7711, CONTACTED RMCC WITH MILLARD BONIN, AIR PRODUCTS 850-995-5337, ON THE LINE. RMCC CONFERRED MILLARD BONIN WITH TOBY TREVETT, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT. MR. THE ADHESIVE PART OF THE TAPE DISSOLVED POSSIBLY FROM THE VAPORS OF THE GASOLINE AS IT EXPANDED DURING TRANSPORT WHICH CONTRIBUTED TO THEIR FAILURE. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT BOTH GLASS RECEPTACLES IN EACH SHIPMENT LEAKED APPROXIMATELY .5 OUNCES INSIDE THE PLASTIC BAGS. column168: E.M.I JOB NUMBER: 17495 TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT HAD PULLED INTO PORT OF ENTRY AND INSPECTOR OBSERVED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID WAS DRIPPING OUT OF THE FRONT TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS IMMEDIATELY MOVED TO THE HAZMAT CONTAINMENT AREA. PORT PERSONNEL THEN NOTIFIED THE IDAHO STATE POLICE AND THE STATE POLICE DISPATCHED THEIR HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM TO THE INCIDENT SITE. CF THEN NOTIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT OF THE INCIDENT. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT DISPATCHED A RESPONSE TEAM FROM OLYMPUS TECHNICAL SERVICES, INC.  WHEN THE  OLYMPUS TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE THEY OBSERVED THAT THE STATE POLICE HAZMAT TEAM HAD UNLOADED THE FREIGHT FROM THE TRAILER THEY HAD BROKEN DOWN THE PALLETS OF ADHESIVE AND IT COULD NOT BE DETERMINED WHICH PAILS WERE FROM WHICH BILL OF LADING. THE OLYMPUS RESPONSE TEAM BEGAN CLEANUP OPERATIONS. THE DAMAGED 5-GALLON METAL CONTAINER HAD LOST ALL OF ITS CONTENTS. THE DAMAGED CONTAINER AND. THE SPILL CLEANUP MATERIAL WERE PLACED INTO A 55-GALLON DRUM. THE REMAINING 5-GALLON CONTAINERS WERE RE-PALLETIZED. THE FREIGHT WAS LOADED ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER ALONG WITH THE DRUM OF SPILL CLEANUP MATERIAL. THIS WOULD BE TRANSPORTED TO THE CF KENT, WA TERMINAL AND DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS WOULD BE MADE AT A LATER TIME. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT NOTIFIED DAVE FEILING (CF REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER) OF THE INCIDENT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RELATED TO THIS INCIDENT.

column168: E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 17451 A DRUM OF MUSTARD OIL WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING ON UNLOADING THE TRAILER. THE LEAK OCCURRED AFTER THE DRUM TIPPED OFF IT'S PALLET AND STRUCK ANOTHER PIECE OF  FREIGHT CAUSING A PIN HOLE NEAR THE DRUM TOP. THE MATERIAL SPILLED HAS A VERY STRONG, ACRID ODOR WHICH CAUSED THE DRIVER TO CALL LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL AND REPORT THE SPILL. A LEVEL A ENTRY WAS MADE TO THE TRAILER, AT WHICH TIME THE DRUM WAS UPRIGHTED AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM. ABSORBENTS WERE APPLIED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND WERE ALSO PLACED IN THE RECOVERY DRUM FOR OFF-SITE DISPOSAL. THE EMPTY TRAILER WAS DROPPED AT THE CLEANUP SUBCONTRACTOR'S FACILITY TO AIR. A PERSISTENT ODOR REMAINED AFTER 48 HOURS, AT WHICH TIME THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS POWERWASHED WITH A CITRUS BASED DETERGENT.

GLEN THOMAS, ICTF SECURITY REPORTED A LIQUID LEAKED FROM THE REAR OF CONTAINER TTNU 337850 AND HAD PUDDLED ON THE GROUND IN STALL EAST 5, SLOT 115.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND STATED HE WAS ON SCENE.  APPROXIMATELY 3-4 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED TO THE PAVEMENT.  THE LOOSE MATERIAL ON THE GROUND WAS CONTAINED, AND THE CONTAINER WAS BEING MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR INSPECTION.  DEVELOPED THE LADING CONSISTED OF DOUBLE STACKED 55 GALLON DRUMS.  BLOCKING AND BRACING APPEARED TO BE ADEQUATE.  INSPECTION WAS NOT ABLE TO DETERMINE WHICH DRUM(S) WERE LEAKING DUE TO THE LOAD CONFIGURATION. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO REMOVE AND INSPECT THE LADING. WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS, IT WAS NOTED THE LAST TWO ROWS OF TOP TIER DRUMS WERE OFF SET WITH PLYWOOD USED FOR BI-LEVEL SEPARATION.  THE PLYWOOD HAD BEEN CUT INTO STRIPS WHICH OVERLAPPED, CAUSING THE THE 2ND COLUMN OF DRUMS FROM THE LEFT WALL TO TILT DUE TO THE UNEVEN SURFACE.  BEYOND THE SECOND ROW OF DRUMS, CARDBOARD HAD BEEN USED AS BI-LEVEL SEPARATION.  THE TOP TIER OF DRUMS CUT INTO THE CARDBOARD DURING TRANSPORTATION CAUSING THEM TO OFF SET AND ABRADE THE ADJACENT DRUMS.  WHILE UNLOADING, LOCATED TWO DRUMS FROM THE TOP TIER THAT HAD LEAKED.  ONE HAD THE TOP CHIME WORN THROUGH, ESTIMATED LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS 10 GALLONS.  THE SECOND DRUM HAD THE TOP ROLLING HOOP WORN THROUGH, ESTIMATED LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS 10 GALLONS.  BOTH DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT.  AN ADDITIONAL 27 DRUMS WERE NOTED WITH DAMAGE THAT DEEMED THEM UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSIT.  AFTER CONSULTING THE SHIPPER, THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE ALSO PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT.  A SECOND CONTAINER, KLFU 181035, WAS BROUGHT IN, AND THE LADING WAS FLOOR LOADED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER, WHICH HAD BEEN CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE SECONDARY CONTAINER, FOR MOVEMENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  RAIL BRIDGE TO HAVE THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER INSPECTED UPON COMPLETION OF THE DELIVERY.

column168: THE RELEASE OCCURRED ON THE EAST SHOULDER OF U.S. HIGHWAY 72, APPROXIMATELY 3.5 MILES SOUTH OF BRIDGER, MONTANA (FIGURE 1). THE RELEASE OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 4:45 AM ON JULY 17,2002 WHEN A TANKER TRUCK PULLING A "PUP" TRAILER WENT OFF THE EAST SIDE OF HIGHWAY 72, CAUSING A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 2,000 GALLONS OF CLEAR DIESEL FROM THE PUP TRAILER. SUBSEQUENT CLEANUP ACTIVITIES BY HINZE, INC. AND HANSER'S AUTOMOTIVE STAFF RECOVERED APPROXIMATELY 1,500 TO 1,700 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM THE PUP TRAILER AND IRRIGATION DITCH. THE RELEASED DIESEL IMMEDIATELY ENTERED A PRIVATE IRRIGATION DITCH LOCATED ADJACENT TO THE WEST SIDE OF HIGHWAY 72 (FIGURE 1). THIS IRRIGATION DITCH PROVIDES WATER TO THE GRASS HAYFIELDS OF THE GRAHAM PROPERTY, LOCATED APPROXIMATELY 0.5 MILES NORTH OF THE RELEASE (FIGURE 1). ON THE DAY OF THE RELEASE, THIS IRRIGATION DITCH WAS ALIGNED SUCH THAT THE WATER WAS ROUTED TO THE NORTHERNMOST FIELD ON THE GRAHAM PROPERTY, LOCATED APPROXIMATELY ONE MILE NORTHEAST OF THE RELEASE POINT (FIGURE 1). MR ROGER WEBBER, THE FARMER WHO LEASES THE GRAHAM FIELDS, NOTICED THE RELEASE SHORTLY AFTER IT OCCURRED ON JULY 17,2002. IN ORDER TO PROTECT THE HAYFIELDS, MR. WEBBER PROMPTLY RE-ROUTED FLOW FROM THE NORTHERNMOST GRAHAM FIELD TO THE WASTEWATER RETURN CANAL LOCATED APPROXIMATELY 1,000 FEET SOUTH OF THIS FIELD (FIGURE 1). THIS PROMPT ACTION MINIMIZED ANY IMPACTS TO THE GRAHAM HAYFIELD. MR. WEBBER THEN MOVED TO THE START OF THE GRAHAM IRRIGATION CANAL, UPSTREAM OF THE RELEASE POINT, AND SHUT OFF THE WATER IN THIS DITCH. THIS PROMPT ACTION MINIMIZED IMPACTS ALONG THE IRRIGATION CANALS. AFTER MR. WEBBER ROUTED THE FLOW TO THE WASTEWATER RETURN CANAL, THE IMPACTED WATER TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 1,300 FEET EAST ALONG THIS WASTEWATER IRRIGATION CANAL TO THE SAND CREEK CANAL (FIGURE 1). THE IMPACTED WATER THEN FLOWED NORTH IN THE SAND CREEK CANAL FOR A DISTANCE OF APPROXIMATELY FIVE MILES. ACCORDING TO MR. LUCK STUDER OF HANSER'S AUTOMOTIVE, IMPACTS WERE NOT OBSERVED IN THE SAND CREEK CANAL BELOW THE POINT WHERE THE CANAL CROSSED THE BORDER OF SECTIONS 16 AND 17, TOWNSHIP 6 SOUTH, RANGE 23 EAST (MR LUKE STUDER, PERSONAL COMMUNICATION, 2002; FIGURE 1). PRODUCT ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE SUBSEQUENTLY PLACED BY HANSER'S STAFF AT SEVERAL LOCATIONS ALONG BOTH THE GRAHAM DITCH AND THE SAND CREED CANAL (FIGURE 1). GRAVEL PILES WERE ALSO PLACED IN THE GRAHAM IRRIGATION DITCH AT POINTS ABOVE, BELOW, AND WITHIN THE RELEASE AREA, SUCH THAT THE IMPACTED MATERIAL WOULD NOT TRAVEL FURTHER WITHIN THIS DITCH THE LOCATIONS OF THESE GRAVEL PILES ARE SHOWN ON FIGURE 1. PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE RELEASE AREA, THE GRAHAM IRRIGATION DITCH AND HAYFIELDS THE WASTEWATER RETURN CANAL, AND THE SAND CREEK CANAL ARE SHOWN IN ATTACHMENT A. WATER SAMPLES WERE COLLECTED BY HANSER'S FOLLOWING THE RELEASE FOR LABORATORY ANALYSIS OF PETROLEUM HYDROCARBONS. THESE WATER SAMPLES WERE COLLECTED FROM BELOW THE FURTHEST DOWNSTREAM BOOM DEPLOYMENT AND FROM JUST BELOW THE RELEASE AREA. THE RESULTS OF THESE A
